found in previous reports. Twenty children, all with Hb SS, died (1.1 deaths per 
100 person-years among SS patients). Infection, most commonly with Streptococcus 
pneumoniae and Hemophilus influenzae, caused 11 deaths. Two children died of 
splenic sequestration, 1 of cerebrovascular accident, and 6 of unclear causes. 
Two patients underwent cholecystectomies, and 17 underwent splenectomies after 
one or more splenic sequestration crises. The experience of this cohort should 
reflect closely the true clinical course of those children with Hb SS and Hb SC 
disease who are observed in sickle cell centers in the United States.

